# Commons backlink: push edits back to agent-commons

Any `.mdc` rule file that carries a `commons_short_code` field in its YAML frontmatter was
sourced from (or pushed to) Agent Commons. That short code is the canonical identifier for
the situation record in the commons corpus.

## Convention

**When you edit a rule that has a `commons_short_code`, also update agent-commons:**

1. Edit the `.mdc` file locally as needed.
2. After the edit is complete (and committed), call:

```
commons_create_situation_with_answer(
  title="<same title as the rule>",
  situation_body_md="<updated rule body>",
  answer_body_md="<resolution / how to apply the rule>",
  tags_json='["cursor-rule", ...]',
  situation_type="rule"
)
```

3. Note the new `short_code` returned and update the `commons_short_code` field in the `.mdc`
   frontmatter if it changed (new entry supersedes old).

> Note: agent-commons entries are **immutable** — a change creates a new answer on the existing
> situation, or a superseding situation. Do not attempt to patch the body in-place.

## Why

Rules pushed to agent-commons are shared across sessions and projects. Editing the local `.mdc`
without updating the corpus means future sessions retrieve stale guidance. The `commons_short_code`
field makes the backlink explicit and machine-checkable.

## Field format

```yaml
---
description: <one-line rule summary>
alwaysApply: true   # or false / globs
commons_short_code: "<8-char alphanumeric code>"
---
```

## Discovering the short code

If a rule file lacks a `commons_short_code` but you believe it was pushed, search:

```
commons_search_situations(query="<rule title>", situation_type="rule", limit=5)
```

Then add the `commons_short_code` to the frontmatter and commit.
